🤖 **Day 20 of My 90 Days of Reinforcement Learning Journey**

Today, I delved into **Policy Gradient Methods** — a foundational concept that shifts the way reinforcement learning agents are trained.

Unlike value-based methods (like DQN), which learn *value functions* and derive a policy indirectly, **Policy Gradient methods learn the policy directly.**

---

### 🧠 **Core Idea:**

We parameterize the policy as ( \pi_\theta(a|s) ) — the probability of taking action *a* in state *s*, given parameters *θ*.
The objective is to **maximize expected cumulative reward**:

[
J(\theta) = E_{\pi_\theta} [R]
]

We then update the parameters in the direction of the gradient:

[
\theta \leftarrow \theta + \alpha \nabla_\theta J(\theta)
]

This approach allows smooth updates and works well in **continuous action spaces**.

---

### 💡 **Why It’s Important:**

* Works directly with stochastic policies
* Enables **continuous control** (unlike discrete-only DQNs)
* Forms the foundation of advanced RL algorithms like **REINFORCE**, **Actor-Critic**, and **PPO**

